{"query": "What actions can be taken on farmland to support invertebrate populations like bees and beetles?", "summary": "Several specific actions can be taken on farmland to support invertebrate populations like bees and beetles. Planting dedicated floral resources on farmland has shown substantial benefits, with fourteen trials in Europe and North America recording substantial numbers of wild bees foraging on perennial or annual sown flowering plants, particularly on patches sown with phacelia where all but one trial found substantial numbers of foraging wild bees and bumblebees, with six trials recording 8-35 bee species (Action ID: 17). Planting nectar flower mixture/wildflower strips has proven effective, with 80 individual studies investigating these strips and 64 showing benefits to wildlife groups, including 50 studies reporting positive effects on invertebrates with increased abundance and species richness (Action ID: 442).

Creating beetle banks provides benefits to farmland biodiversity, with fourteen reports from eight studies finding positive effects on invertebrate densities, distribution, and higher ground beetle density and species diversity in spring and summer, though effects varied between specific grass species and invertebrate groups (Action ID: 651). Managing the agricultural landscape to enhance floral resources shows promise, with one large replicated controlled trial demonstrating that long-tongued bumblebee abundance on field margins was positively correlated with the number of pollen and nectar agri-environment agreements in a 10 km grid square (Action ID: 362).

Reducing chemical inputs supports invertebrate populations, with studies on restricting certain pesticides showing that using specific fungicides reduced chick food insect abundance less than others (Action ID: 565). Reducing pesticide or fertilizer use through organic farming methods has shown some benefits, with studies finding increased wood mouse abundance when pesticides were reduced, though effects varied by species (Action ID: 2539). Managing grassland through reduced cutting frequency benefits pollinators, with studies finding that meadows cut once per year had higher species richness of butterflies and other pollinators compared to meadows cut two or more times per year (Action ID: 3961). Similarly, reducing grazing intensity by seasonal removal of livestock has shown benefits, with studies finding grasslands where cattle were removed in summer had higher abundance of butterflies and other pollinators than grasslands grazed throughout the summer (Action ID: 3960).", "action_ids": ["17","651","442","362","565","2539","3961","3960"]}

